\begin_layout Proof
It is clear that 
\begin_inset Formula $(1)\implies(2)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(1)\implies(3)$
\end_inset

.
 We will prove 
\begin_inset Formula $(2)\implies(1)$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $(3)\implies(2)$
\end_inset

 follows similarly.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
To see 
\begin_inset Formula $(2)\implies(1)$
\end_inset

, it is enough to show 
\begin_inset Formula $J^{u}$
\end_inset

 is a parallel Jacobi field where 
\begin_inset Formula $J^{u}(t)$
\end_inset

 is a unstable Jacobi field along 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{v}(t)$
\end_inset

.
 Notice that 
\begin_inset Formula $J^{u}(t)$
\end_inset

 satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula $J^{u}(0)=w\in T_{\pi v}H^{u}(v)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(J^{u})^{'}(0)=0$
\end_inset

 (because 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda^{u}(v)=0$
\end_inset

).
 Similarly, for any 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau\in\R$
\end_inset

 we have a unstable Jacobi field 
\begin_inset Formula $J_{\tau}^{u}(t)$
\end_inset

 along 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{f_{\tau}v}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $J_{\tau}^{u}(0)=w_{\tau}=P_{\tau}w\in T_{\pi f_{\tau}v}H^{u}(f_{\tau}v)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(J_{\tau}^{u})^{'}(0)=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof

\series bold
Claim:
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $J_{\tau}^{u}(t)=J^{u}(\tau+t)$
\end_inset

 for any 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau,t\in\R$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
We first recall that 
\begin_inset Formula $J^{u}$
\end_inset

 satisfies the equation 
\begin_inset Formula $(J^{u})^{'}(t)={\cal U}^{u}(t)J^{u}(t)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal U}^{u}(t)$
\end_inset

 is the second fundamental form of 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{u}(v)$
\end_inset

, and similarly we have 
\begin_inset Formula $(J_{\tau}^{u})^{'}(t)={\cal U}^{u}(\tau+t)J_{\tau}^{u}(t)$
\end_inset

.
 This shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $J^{u}(t+\tau)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $J_{\tau}^{u}(t)$
\end_inset

 satisfies the same equation 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{J'(x)}{J(x)}={\cal U}^{u}(x)$
\end_inset

; moreover, since 
\begin_inset Formula $\dim M=2$
\end_inset

 we also know 
\begin_inset Formula $J^{u}(\tau)=P_{\tau}w=J_{\tau}^{u}(0)$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $J_{\tau}^{u}(t)=J^{u}(\tau+t)$
\end_inset

 for any 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau,t\in\R$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
By the claim, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $(J{}^{u})''(t)=(J_{t}^{u})''(0)=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in\R$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

