\begin_layout Lemma
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "lem:lamb_T_and_sing"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\lt(v)=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $v\in\mathrm{Sing}$
\end_inset

.
 
\color red
(Can be simplified!!!)
\end_layout

\begin_layout --Separator--

\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
The if direction is clear.
 In the following we prove the only if direction.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
First we notice that since 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 is nonnegative, continuous, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lt(v)\geq\int_{-T}^{T}\lambda(f_{t}v)dt\geq0$
\end_inset

, we have that 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{T}(v)=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $T\in\R$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda(f_{t}v)=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in\R$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof

\series bold
Claim:
\series default
 There are only three possible cases such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda(f_{t}v)=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in\R$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{itemize}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

[font=
\backslash
normalfont]
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
item[(i)]
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda^{s}(f_{t}v)=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in\R$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
item[(ii)]
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda^{u}(f_{t}v)=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in\R$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
item[(iii)]
\end_layout

\end_inset

 There exists 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{0}\in\R$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda^{s}(f_{t_{0}}v)=\lambda^{u}(f_{t_{0}}v)=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{itemize}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
It is clear from Lemma 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "lem:3.3"

\end_inset

 that both 
\begin_inset Formula $({\rm i})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $({\rm ii})$
\end_inset

 give 
\begin_inset Formula $v\in{\rm Sing}$
\end_inset

.
 To see 
\begin_inset Formula $({\rm iii})$
\end_inset

 also implies 
\begin_inset Formula $v\in{\rm Sing}$
\end_inset

, we recall that, for 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\in\{s,u\}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda^{\sigma}(f_{t_{0}}v)=0$
\end_inset

 implies that there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $0\neq w^{\sigma}\in T_{\pi(f_{t_{0}}v)}H^{\sigma}(f_{t_{0}}v)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal U}^{\sigma}(w^{\sigma})=0$
\end_inset

 .
 Since both 
\begin_inset Formula $w^{u},w^{s}$
\end_inset

 are tangent to 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{t_{0}}v$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\dim M=2$
\end_inset

, we know 
\begin_inset Formula $w^{u}=w^{s}$
\end_inset

 (by taking same length).
 It is not hard to see that the 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{u}(f_{t_{0}}v)-$
\end_inset

 Jacobi field 
\begin_inset Formula $J^{u}$
\end_inset

 matches the 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{s}(f_{t_{0}}v)-$
\end_inset

 Jacobi field 
\begin_inset Formula $J^{s}$
\end_inset

, that implies, 
\begin_inset Formula $E^{u}(f_{t_{0}}v)\cap E^{v}(f_{t_{0}}v)\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 Thus we have 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{t_{0}}v\in\Sing$
\end_inset

, and because 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sing$
\end_inset

 is flow invariant we have 
\begin_inset Formula $v\in\Sing.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
To see the claim, let 
\begin_inset Formula $U:=\{t\in\R:\ \lambda^{u}(f_{t}v)=0\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S:=\{t\in\R:\ \lambda^{s}(f_{t}v)=0\}$
\end_inset

.
 Since both 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda^{u},\lambda^{s}$
\end_inset

 are continuous, 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 are closed sets in 
\begin_inset Formula $\R$
\end_inset

.
 Notice that if 
\begin_inset Formula $U\cap S=\emptyset$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $U=\R\backslash S$
\end_inset

; thus 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 are clopen sets.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\R$
\end_inset

 is connected, we have when 
\begin_inset Formula $U\cap S=\emptyset$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $U=\R$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $S=\R$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

